  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Deborah Weston writes that Wendell Phillips came to New Bedford Saturday night [April 23] and stayed with Andrew Robeson. Deborah said about Phillips&apos;s lecture: &quot;We had taken a great deal of pain to notify the churches.&quot; She recounts the reaction of the ministers. Silas Hawley was distressed that the lecture could not be held in his church. Liberty Hall was thronged and Phillips&apos;s lecture was much admired. The Whigs were displeased with his attack on Edward Everett. Charles Congdon is editor of the [New Bedford?] Bulletin, &quot;a born democrat, but who changed to Whiggery for the sake of his subscription list.&quot; Deborah wants to know what Mr. [Joshua] Bates wrote to Warren Weston. She gives the names of men who have failed in business. Deborah comments about the economy: &quot;All people talk about is who comes next.&quot; Deborah would like to have little Henry Chapman sent to her, if his parents should consider going to Northampton.</subfield>
